        "decorator": "none",
        "content": "<h3 style=\"text-align:center\">Safety stock is emergency stock meant to help you account for emergency circumstances &ndash; any circumstances that can cause you to run out of product. Some examples are breakdowns of production machinery, aweather-related troubles affecting your stock or deliveries, unpredicted surges in your product&#39;s popularity leaving your supplier unable to match demands- basically, anything unexpected.</h3>\n\n<p>Supply chain problems happen, and as a retail business, you need to be prepared to face them. Backorders work, but they come with the risk of losing sales and customer loyalty. So, how do you protect your business against unexpected incidents without upsetting customers and compromising your professional reputation? This is where calculating safety stock comes in handy.&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\nSo, what is safety stock? Safety stock is an inventory formula retailers use to determine the emergency stock needed to keep on hand. This is the extra stock of products they need to have in case of unforeseen circumstances that can put them on the verge of selling out. You need to have enough product to weather storms, but not so much so that you end up with carrying costs that are too high for your sales level. While this sounds straightforward, the trick is to know how to calculate inventory in order to determine the optimal stocking level. It&#39;s important to remember that sales don&#39;t only have to cover the sold products&#39; own carrying costs, but the carrying costs of the safety stock as well.&nbsp;</p>\n",
