        "title": "Calculating safety stock formula - inventory equation",
        "h1": null,
        "style": "dark",
        "decorator": "none",
        "content": "<p><strong>How do you calculate safety stock?&nbsp;</strong><br />\n<br />\nSafety stock calculation is simple. You just need to have your purchase and sales orders data available. Once you do, use this simple safety stock formula, also known as the &quot;inventory equation&quot;:&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\n<strong>Safety stock = (Maximum daily usage * Maximum lead time in days) &ndash; (Average daily usage * Average lead time in days).&nbsp;</strong><br />\n<br />\nHere&#39;s a retailer&#39;s inventory formula example to illustrate how the safety stock calculator works:&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\nA souvenir retailer, &quot;From Russia With Love&quot; based in New York City sells Gzel tea sets from Russia. On average, it takes about 40 (average lead time in days) days to get the tea sets made and shipped from Russia to NYC. The company sells about 15 sets a day (average daily usage), but on good days sales can go as high as 25 (maximum daily usage). Unfortunately, in Russia, there is often heavy snow and roads are not always reliable, which sometimes results in longer lead times, up to 55 days (maximum lead time in days).&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\nNow, how do we calculate inventory? Using the safety stock equation above, their optimal stocking level formula would be:&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\n(25 x 55) - (15 x 40) = 775&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\nWith this, we have determined that the From Russia With Love souvenir store would always need to carry about 775 tea sets as safety stock (especially in winter when the weather conditions in Russia are harsh).&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\nThis is basically all there is to know about how to calculate safety stock. Your stock holding formula will help your business navigate safely through all the fluctuations in demand and lead time.&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\nDepending on the products you&#39;re selling, you may need to adjust that stock holding formula to seasonal changes. During peak seasons, sales may increase drastically requiring more safety stock. But once the peak season is over, you would want to start reducing your safety stock levels to lower your carrying costs.&nbsp;</p>\n",
